  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much would it roughly cost to start a new car company?",
  "response": "Starting a new car company is a complex and expensive endeavor. The costs can vary greatly depending on several factors, such as the type of vehicles you plan to produce, the scale of production, the location of your facilities, and whether you are starting from scratch or acquiring an existing company. Here's a rough breakdown of some of the key costs involved:\n\n1. **Research and Development (R&D):**\n   - Developing a new vehicle from scratch can cost anywhere from $1 billion to $3 billion. This includes designing the car, developing the technology, and testing prototypes.\n\n2. **Manufacturing Facilities:**\n   - Building a new manufacturing plant can cost between $1 billion and $2 billion, depending on the size and location. You may also need to invest in equipment and machinery, which can add hundreds of millions of dollars to the total.\n\n3. **Supply Chain and Logistics:**\n   - Establishing a supply chain and logistics network can cost several hundred million dollars. This includes sourcing materials, setting up distribution channels, and managing inventory.\n\n4. **Regulatory Compliance and Certifications:**\n   - Meeting safety, emissions, and other regulatory requirements can cost tens of millions of dollars per vehicle model. This includes crash testing, emissions testing, and obtaining necessary certifications.\n\n5. **Marketing and Branding:**\n   - Launching a new car brand and marketing your vehicles can cost hundreds of millions of dollars. This includes advertising, PR, and dealer network development.\n\n6. **Working Capital:**\n   - You will need sufficient working capital to cover operating expenses until your company becomes profitable. This can range from several hundred million to over a billion dollars, depending on your business model and production scale.\n\n**Total Estimated Cost:**\n- A rough estimate to start a new car company from scratch, including all the above factors, could be in the range of $2 billion to $5 billion or more.\n\nThese figures are rough estimates and can vary significantly based on specific circumstances. It's also worth noting that many new car companies opt for different strategies, such as focusing on electric vehicles, partnering with existing manufacturers, or starting with niche markets to reduce initial costs.",
